node.text:
This monumental painting represents the changing urban milieu of late 19th-century Paris. The artist Caillebotte strikingly captured a vast, stark modernity, complete with life-size figures strolling in the foreground and wearing the latest fashions.

Take a closer look in the latest episode of our Art Institute Essentials Tour.

node.text:
To Vincent van Gogh, this picture of his bedroom symbolized relaxation and peace. However, to our eyes the canvas seems to teem with nervous energy and turmoil—an effect heightened by the sharply receding perspective.

Take a closer look at "The Bedroom" (1889)—part of our Art Institute Essentials series.

In the paintings of Picasso’s Blue Period (1901-04), the artist restricted himself to a cold, monochromatic blue palette, flattened forms, and emotional, psychological themes of human misery and alienation. This painting reﬂects the then twenty-two-year-old Picasso’s personal struggle and sympathy for the plight of the downtrodden.

On this episode of Art Institute Essentials Tour, take a closer look at "The Old Guitarist," painted by Picasso between late 1903 and early 1904.

Working out of a repurposed Chicago Railway Systems electrical substation built in 1909, artist Richard Hunt has space to be able to continuously create both towering sculptures and more intimate constructions.

Developed intuitively, Hunt's works emerge from a shape visualized in his mind, cut into metal, and welded together in a process that can continue for many years. His sculptures embody a form of improvisation, an ever-unfolding dialogue that occurs, in the artist’s words, "between me, the technique, and the material."

See the exhibition "Richard Hunt: Scholar’s Rock or Stone of Hope or Love of Bronze" before it closes September 20. (Link in bio for more info)

node.text:
Among the 24 works shown by Edgar Degas at the second Impressionist exhibition, in 1876, were several ballet scenes, including “Yellow Dancers.”

Three ballerinas preen in the foreground of this radical composition. Absorbed in the task of adjusting their costumes, they are bathed in light that seems to be filtered through golden gauze. The dancers’ forms echo the shape of the stage flat behind them; beyond that artificial barrier, we glimpse the truncated calves and feet of a number of dancers.

In Degas's painting, the viewer is placed in the wings, in the position of an abonné, an elite male subscriber to the Paris Opéra who paid for the special privilege to freely roam and socialize backstage. As with the racetracks, Degas invoked the help of influential friends to grant him access to this private world, and he would be an abonné himself in 1885.

See more than 10 works by Degas now on view and explore over 100 works by the artist in the museum's collection. (Link in bio)

node.text:
In this work on paper by Antonio Pollaiuolo, a group of men, arranged more or less symmetrically, engage in violent combat against a background of dense vegetation.

While the reason for their fighting is unknown, this unusually large engraving was the most influential Italian print of the 15th century, engendering numerous copies and emulations.

Pollaiuolo, a goldsmith and sculptor, probably executed it to advertise his skills in metalworking as well as his ability to convincingly depict the nude male body in motion, a central concern of Italian Renaissance artists.

See "Battle of the Naked Men" (1489–95) on view in Gallery 204.

node.text:
Chicago landscape architect Franz Lipp created these fantastical studies in 1928 for an open-air theater in Highland Park, Illinois.

Lipp's design shows a vivid scene of the theater in use, framed by a towering ring of clipped hedges that recalls both the hemispherical form of open-air theaters in antiquity and the pillars of Stonehenge. He evoked another traditional model with the plan for the site, which mimics a neoclassical urn filled with flowers.

Although this project was never realized, Lipp brought similarly dramatic and monumental visions to many projects in the Chicago suburbs, from cemeteries to corporate headquarters.

See these works by Franz Lipp on view in Gallery 285.
